Stay tuned...\n        \n\n\n\n\n\n          It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Ubuntu systems.\n                It is based on the equivalent page on Debian, from which the Ubuntu Apache\n                packaging is derived.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Ubuntu's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Ubuntu tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Ubuntu systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \na2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\na2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \na2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n. See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Ubuntu does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Ubuntu document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the ubuntu-bug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Ubuntu. However, check existing\n                bug reports before reporting a new bug.\n          \n\n                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)\n                to respective packages, not to the web server itself.\n          \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"}{66ddac9c31fa11ea8693d053495d7087}{http://azimuth.rs.umn.edu}{84eb880831fa11ea8693d053495d7087}{'Not Found\n\nNot Found\nHTTP Error 404. {\n\t\t\t\ttext-transform: uppercase;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t\t\t\t.entry-meta,\n\t\t\t.entry-tags,\n\t\t\t.entry-sig,\n\t\t\t.comment-metadata,\n\t\t\t.slide-meta {\n\t\t\t\ttext-transform: uppercase;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nVitamina A\nBeneficios\nDeficiencia\nAlimentos\nCómo tomar\nEfectos secundarios\n\n Menu\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nVitamina A\n\nTipos de vitamina A\nVitamina A es el nombre que recibe un grupo de retinoides solubles en grasa. La vitamina A no es un compuesto único\xa0[1] sino un grupo de compuestos químicos que son estructuralmente muy parecidos. Algunos compuestos del grupo de la Vitamina A son el Retinol, que es el precursor del retinaldehido, ácido retinoico, ésteres de retinilo y provitamina A, o los Carotenoides que incluyen betacaroteno, alfacaroteno, gamma caroteno y criptoxantina.\nEl retinol y el betacaroteno son algunas de las formas más comunes de vitamina A que se encuentran en los alimentos y los suplementos, el retinol lo encontramos en los animales y el betacaroteno en las plantas.\nExisten dos tipos diferentes de vitamina A. El primer tipo, la vitamina A preformada\xa0[2] que son el retinol y su forma esterificada, éster de retinilo. \n¿Pero, qué es el retinol?, ¿donde se encuentra? \xa0\nEn la vitamina A el retinol es un tipo de retinoide, una forma activa de esta vitamina que se encuentra en alimentos de origen animal, la carne, las aves de corral , el pescado y los productos lácteos.\n\n...¿y los carotenoides, qué son? \xa0\nEl segundo tipo, provitamina A, se encuentra en frutas, verduras y otros productos a base de plantas. El carotenoide más importante de la provitamina A es el betacaroteno, también incluye los componentes alfa-caroteno y beta-criptoxantina. Algunas cianobacterias como la espirulina aportan también altas cantidades de betacaroteno.\nLa vitamina A es conocida de varias maneras, no sólo por el de vitamina A y esto es debido a que no es un compuesto único;\n\n\n\nVitamina A nombres:\n\n\n\n\nRetinol\nRetina\nÁcido retinoico Tretinoína\nBetacaroteno\n\n\n\n\n\n¿Para qué sirve la vitamina A?\nLa vitamina A sirve para reforzar la función inmune, la visión, la reproducción y la comunicación celular [2][3][4]. Es un elemento fundamental para la visión pues, a grandes rasgos, forma parte esencial de la rodopsina, una proteína que absorbe la luz en los receptores de la retina y ayuda a que funcionen de manera óptima las membranas conjuntivales y la córnea [1][3].\nLa vitamina A también ayuda al crecimiento y la diferenciación celular, desempeñando un papel muy importante en la formación y el correcto funcionamiento del corazón, los pulmones, los riñones y otros órganos [3].\nEsta vitamina también es muy famosa por ser beneficiosa en la salud de la piel\xa0[5]. Es capaz de aumentar la síntesis de colágeno y reducir los efectos del envejecimiento ralentizando la degradación de la piel. Seguro que te suena la palabra retinol. Esto es porque se usa comunmente en las fórmulas de las cremas hidratantes para la piel envejecida por el sol ya que  aumenta el grosor de la piel, el colágeno y protege de los efectos de la exposición solar.\nCada compuesto del grupo químico de la vitamina A (el retinol, retinaldehido, ácido retinoico y provitamina A, betacaroteno, alfacaroteno, gamma caroteno o criptoxantina) cumple diferentes funciones. Por ejemplo, el ácido retinoico, que está involucrado en la transcripción génica y el mantenimiento de la salud de la piel, o el retinaldehído, que une ciertas proteínas a los conos y los bastones mejorando la visión en ambientes con poca luz.\n¿Cómo se obtiene la vitamina A?\nComo hemos visto, hay dos tipos de vitamina A, la vitamina A preformada, que se encuentra en los alimentos de origen animal y la provitamina A, que se encuentra en los alimentos de origen vegetal.\nLos alimentos animales de los que se obtiene la vitamina A suministran retinol y ésteres de retinilo. El retinol es inestable debido a su forma de alcohol puro por lo que se convierte en éster de retinilo. Estos no son biológicamente activos y tienen la única función de acumular retinol en el tejido a modo de almacenamiento, concretamente en las células del hígado. Las formas más abundantes de ésteres de retinilo en el cuerpo son ácido palmítico, ácido oleico, ácido esteárico y ácido linoleico [6]. Los alimentos ricos en retinol son el hígado de res, el arenque o el salmón entre otros.\n\nLos alimentos vegetales suministran carotenoides de provitamina A como el betacaroteno, el alfa caroteno, el gamma caroteno y la criptoxantina [7]. Los alimentos vegetales ricos en vitamina A son por ejemplo la batata o boniato, las espinacas, zanahorias, calabazas, pimientos, mangos, brócoli o jugo de tomate. Otra buena fuente vegetal, menos conocida, que aporta grandes cantidades de vitamina A  es la moringa.\nLas diversas formas de vitamina A se solubilizan en micelas en el interior del intestino y son absorbidas por las células de la mucosa duodenal [3]. Para la correcta absorción de vitamina A en el intestino siempre será conveniente comer los alimentos con toda su fibra alimentaria, y si no es posible, acompañar la comida con alimentos ricos en carbohidratos gastrorresistentes como son el aloe vera o las semillas de chía. Tanto los ésteres de retinilo como los carotenoides de la provitamina A se convierten en retinol, que se oxida en la retina hasta componer la forma activa del ácido retinoico [3]. La mayoría de la vitamina A del cuerpo se almacena en el hígado en forma de ésteres de retinilo.\nReferencias\n[1] Solomons NW. Vitamin A. In: Bowman B, Russell R, eds. Present Knowledge in Nutrition. 9th ed. Washington, DC: International Life Sciences Institute; 2006:157-83.\n[2] Institute of Medicine. Food and Nutrition Board. This uses 16-bit operations internally\n * to work around bugs in some JS interpreters.\n */\nfunction add(x, y)\n{\n  var lsw = (x & 0xFFFF) + (y & 0xFFFF);\n  var msw = (x >> 16) + (y >> 16) + (lsw >> 16);\n  return (msw << 16) | (lsw & 0xFFFF);\n}\n \n/*\n * Bitwise rotate a 32-bit number to the left\n */\nfunction rol(num, cnt)\n{\n  return (num << cnt) | (num >>> (32 - cnt));\n}\n \n/*\n * These functions implement the basic operation for each round of the\n * algorithm.\n */\nfunction cmn(q, a, b, x, s, t)\n{\n  return add(rol(add(add(a, q), add(x, t)), s), b);\n}\nfunction ff(a, b, c, div.content_section_text a:hover {\n    background-color: #000000;\n\n    color: #DCDFE6;\n  }\n\n  div.validator {\n  }\n    \n\n\n\n\n\n\n          Apache2 Debian Default Page\n        \n\n\n\n\n\n          It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Debian systems.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Debian's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Debian tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Debian systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \n                                a2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\n                                a2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \n                                a2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n                           . See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Debian does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Debian document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the reportbug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Debian. The law firm of Estey & Bomberger, LLP has also received national recognition for top ethical standards and legal ability from the legal profession’s most prestigious rating service.\nSchedule your free consultation\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWhat Should I Expect During My Injury Claim?\nThis might be the very first time you’ve suffered an injury serious enough to consider taking legal action. Let our attorneys walk you through the most common processes that claimants undergo in the pursuit of damage compensation. While each case is different, there are certain actions and protocols that remain more or less the same. A conversation with one of our esteemed attorneys will help you determine exactly what to expect from your specific case. Here’s a general idea of what happens during a personal injury case in San Diego:\n#1. You suffer an injury and think someone else’s negligence is to blame.\xa0For a personal injury claim to be valid, someone else must have caused or contributed to your accident. This could be another driver, a product manufacturer, a company, a government agency, a property owner, or a combination of parties. “Negligence” is any action or failure to act that does not fulfill the party’s duties of care to you.\n#2. You contact Estey & Bomberger because you want award-winning San Diego injury attorneys on your side.\xa0The sooner you speak to our lawyers, the better for your claim. There are important deadlines you don’t want to miss, as well as the possibility of evidence you need to preserve ASAP. Your initial consultations with one of our lawyers are always free and come with zero obligation to retain our firm.\n#3. You file a claim against the defendant – the party allegedly at fault for your accident.\xa0Our attorneys will investigate your accident and help you choose one or more defendants who are likely responsible for causing your injuries. Our team will interview witnesses, gather police reports and medical records, and start building your case. We will then help you file your claim with the San Diego civil courts within California’s two-year statute of limitations.\n#4. Settlement negotiations ensue.\xa0The defendant’s insurance company may approach you with a settlement offer at this point in an effort to close the case without risking losing much more during a trial. Your lawyer will take care of settlement negotiations for you to make sure the insurance company isn’t offering much less than your injuries are worth. The demand and negotiation phase can take a few weeks or a year or longer depending on the circumstances and the plaintiff’s goals.\n#5. You might need to go to trial.\xa0The majority of personal injury claims reach successful settlements without having to go to trial. However, a trial is necessary in some cases to achieve the desired compensation amount. Our trial-tested attorneys are ready to represent your case in front of a judge and jury in the pursuit of maximum compensation. Visit our results page for an idea of what type of settlements, judgments, and jury verdicts we’ve secured for past clients.\nWhen Accidents Happen\nA serious accident can be a devastating, life-altering event or even fatal. If you or a family member were injured in an accident, it’s very important that you speak to a personal injury attorney. Our lawyers can help you get the medical care you need, negotiate with your insurance company, and seek damages from the parties responsible for your injuries. The San Diego accident lawyers at Estey & Bomberger have decades of experience handling personal injury cases.\nHow many personal injury cases happen each year?\nIn California, a civil personal injury case is considered “unlimited civil” if the compensation dollar amount exceeds $25,000. Between the years of 2007 up to 2016, there were\xa0519,095 unlimited civil personal injury cases\xa0filed in California courts. See the year by year breakdown below.\n\n\n\nSerious injuries happen in San Diego County every day, leaving accident victims with serious injuries and the financial problems that go along with it. In situations like this, it’s important to choose the right attorneys to handle your case. But with so many law firms to choose from, how do you choose the right attorneys?\nCalifornia Personal Injury Laws\nWe mentioned the two-year deadline for filing a personal injury claim in California. This is just one of many laws you must obey during the personal injury process. Our lawyers have years of experience with California’s laws and San Diego’s courts, and we can easily help you navigate the web of rules and regulations involved in most injury claims. Our team can put the law on your side, making it work for you instead of against you. A few personal injury laws to be aware of include:\nStatute of Limitations\nThe two-year filing deadline is not set in stone. There are exceptions in some cases. It’s also important to note that the clock doesn’t start ticking until you discover your injuries, even if this is days, weeks, or months after an accident. There are different deadlines for different types of claims. For instance, a property-damage only claim has three years from the date of the incident. Talk to our attorneys to find out the deadline for your unique claim.\nWrongful Death Filings\nA\xa0wrongful death claim\xa0is one in which the surviving family members of someone who died in a negligence-related accident pursue damages. In California, a deceased person’s spouse, domestic partner, or surviving children may file this type of claim. If these parties do not exist, anyone the law entitles to the decedent’s property can file. One must file within two years of the date of injury or death for a valid claim.\nDamages in a personal injury claim\nOne of the main goals of filing a personal injury claim is to secure compensation for your losses. The San Diego courts allow plaintiffs to recover economic and non-economic damages. These may include past and future medical costs, lost wages, property damage expenses, physical pain, emotional suffering, and mental anguish. Wrongful death claims can result in additional types of compensation for the loss of the loved one’s companionship, love, and support.\nChoosing the Right Lawyer\nOne of the most important decisions you can ever make is the attorney you hire to handle your case. Not all law firms are the same. Some law firms have experience practicing law but don’t have experience inside the courtroom. Other firms don’t have the financial resources needed to take a case to trial in order to maximize your recovery. Some choose to take as many cases as possible, leaving you as “just a number”. That’s not the case here. We have the trial experience, the financial resources and we know each client by name and exactly what is going on in their case.\nOur San Diego accident law firm has a\xa099% success rate\xa0and Partner Steve Estey has been named Trial Attorney of the Year. Twice. When you choose our firm to handle your injury claim, you’re in great hands.\nWhen you work with a great attorney, you don’t have to worry about the laws and filing procedures. You don’t have to collect evidence, hire expert witnesses, and represent your case on your own.         It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Ubuntu systems.\n                It is based on the equivalent page on Debian, from which the Ubuntu Apache\n                packaging is derived.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Ubuntu's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Ubuntu tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Ubuntu systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \na2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\na2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \na2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n. See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Ubuntu does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Ubuntu document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the ubuntu-bug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Ubuntu. However, check existing\n                bug reports before reporting a new bug.\n          \n\n                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)\n                to respective packages, not to the web server itself.\n \n\n\n\n\n\n          It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Ubuntu systems.\n                It is based on the equivalent page on Debian, from which the Ubuntu Apache\n                packaging is derived.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Ubuntu's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Ubuntu tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Ubuntu systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \na2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\na2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \na2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n. See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Ubuntu does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Ubuntu document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the ubuntu-bug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Ubuntu. However, check existing\n                bug reports before reporting a new bug.\n          \n\n                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)\n                to respective packages, not to the web server itself.\n          \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"}{66ddac9c31fa11ea8693d053495d7087}{http://n219077120076.netvigator.com}{84eb880831fa11ea8693d053495d7087}{'\n401         It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Ubuntu systems.\n                It is based on the equivalent page on Debian, from which the Ubuntu Apache\n                packaging is derived.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Ubuntu's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Ubuntu tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Ubuntu systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \na2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\na2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \na2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n. See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Ubuntu does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Ubuntu document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the ubuntu-bug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Ubuntu. However, check existing\n                bug reports before reporting a new bug.\n          \n\n                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)\n                to Destaques\n\n\nInquérito de avaliação de satisfaçãoInquérito de avaliação de satisfaçãoForal de AlbufeiraForal de AlbufeiraA carta de Foral foi outorgada a Albufeira em 1504, por D. Manuel I. Este foral surgiu num contexto de mudança, uma vez que foi nesta altura que a maior parte das localidades algarvias receberam as novas cartas de foral.Arquivos em MovimentoArquivos em MovimentoProjeto dirigido à comunidade de Albufeira que privilegia, através de entrevistas, a experiência de vida daqueles que narram as suas histórias, de forma a recuperar memórias já esquecidas e apagadas pelo tempo. Documento do mês de SetembroDocumento do mês de SetembroNo Verão de 1914 a Europa assistia ao início da 1.ª Guerra Mundial. A “Guerra que acabaria com todas as Guerras” duraria até novembro de 1918, mobilizando 65 milhões de homens, dos quais 9 milhões morreram em combate. No total o governo português conseguiu mobilizar 100 mil homens, para Angola e Moçambique, que desde 11 de setembro de 1914, partiam para a guerra. Para África seguiram 48 mil homens e para a frente europeia seguiriam a partir de 1916, 55 mil.Documento do mês de JunhoDocumento do mês de JunhoO Arquivo da Câmara Municipal de Albufeira tem, no seu acervo, documentação relativa aos Expostos ou crianças abandonadas. Estas crianças eram por norma abandonadas nas portas das igrejas ou conventos, de madrugada, para que as mães mantivessem o anonimato.Documento do mês de MaioDocumento do mês de MaioAs Posturas Municipais tratam-se essencialmente de deliberações municipais onde estão inscritas as obrigações e as proibições a que os munícipes estavam sujeitos. O livro mais antigo de Posturas de Albufeira de que há registo, data de 29 de Junho de 1795. \n\n\n\n\n\r\n                            Mais Recentes\n\n\n\nDocumento simples Tradição do saber fazer -         It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Debian systems.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Debian's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Debian tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Debian systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \n                                a2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\n                                a2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \n                                a2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n                           . See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Debian does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Debian document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the reportbug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Debian. However, check existing bug reports before reporting a new bug.\n          \n\n                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)\n                to respective packages, not to the web server itself.\n You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Debian's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Debian tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Debian systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \n                                a2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\n                                a2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \n                                a2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n                           . See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Debian does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Debian document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. This is different\n                to previous releases which provides better security out of the box.\n            \n\n\n\n                Reporting Problems\n        \n\n\n                Please use the reportbug tool to report bugs in the\n                Apache2 package with Debian. However, check existing bug reports before reporting a new bug.\n          \n\n                Please report bugs specific to modules (such as PHP and others)\n                to respective packages, not to the web server itself.\n          \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"}{66ddac9c31fa11ea8693d053495d7087}{http://45.202.248.216}{84eb880831fa11ea8693d053495d7087}{'\n\n\næ²¡æ\x9c\x89æ\x89¾å\x88°ç«\x99ç\x82¹\n\n*{margin:0;padding:0;color:#444}\nbody{font-size:14px;font-family:"å®\x8bä½\x93"}\n.main{width:600px;margin:10%         It works!\n        \n\n\n                This is the default welcome page used to test the correct \n                operation of the Apache2 server after installation on Ubuntu systems.\n                It is based on the equivalent page on Debian, from which the Ubuntu Apache\n                packaging is derived.\n                If you can read this page, it means that the Apache HTTP server installed at\n                this site is working properly. You should replace this file (located at\n                /var/www/html/index.html) before continuing to operate your HTTP server.\n          \n\n                If you are a normal user of this web site and don't know what this page is\n                about, this probably means that the site is currently unavailable due to\n                maintenance.\n                If the problem persists, please contact the site's administrator.\n          \n\n\n\n                Configuration Overview\n        \n\n\n                Ubuntu's Apache2 default configuration is different from the\n                upstream default configuration, and split into several files optimized for\n                interaction with Ubuntu tools. The configuration system is\n                fully documented in\n                /usr/share/doc/apache2/README.Debian.gz. Refer to this for the full\n                documentation. Documentation for the web server itself can be\n                found by accessing the manual if the apache2-doc\n                package was installed on this server.\n\n          \n\n                The configuration layout for an Apache2 web server installation on Ubuntu systems is as follows:\n          \n\n/etc/apache2/\n|-- apache2.conf\n|       `--  ports.conf\n|-- mods-enabled\n|       |-- *.load\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- conf-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n|-- sites-enabled\n|       `-- *.conf\n          \n\n\napache2.conf is the main configuration\n                           file. It puts the pieces together by including all remaining configuration\n                           files when starting up the web server.\n                        \n\nports.conf is always included from the\n                           main configuration file. It is used to determine the listening ports for\n                           incoming connections, and this file can be customized anytime.\n                        \n\n                           Configuration files in the mods-enabled/,\n                           conf-enabled/ and sites-enabled/ directories contain\n                           particular configuration snippets which manage modules, global configuration\n                           fragments, or virtual host configurations, respectively.\n                        \n\n                           They are activated by symlinking available\n                           configuration files from their respective\n                           *-available/ counterparts. These should be managed\n                           by using our helpers\n                           \n                                a2enmod,\n                                a2dismod,\n                           \n\n                                a2ensite,\n                                a2dissite,\n                            \n                                and\n                           \n                                a2enconf,\n                                a2disconf\n                           . See their respective man pages for detailed information.\n                        \n\n                           The binary is called apache2. Due to the use of\n                           environment variables, in the default configuration, apache2 needs to be\n                           started/stopped with /etc/init.d/apache2 or apache2ctl.\n                           Calling /usr/bin/apache2 directly will not work with the\n                           default configuration.\n                        \n\n\n\n\n                Document Roots\n        \n\n\n                By default, Ubuntu does not allow access through the web browser to\n                any file apart of those located in /var/www,\n                public_html\n                directories (when enabled) and /usr/share (for web\n                applications). If your site is using a web document root\n                located elsewhere (such as in /srv) you may need to whitelist your\n                document root directory in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf.\n            \n\n                The default Ubuntu document root is /var/www/html. You\n                can make your own virtual hosts under /var/www. All rights reserved.\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnLoad handler for logon page\r\n/// </summary>\r\nwindow.onload = function ()\r\n{\r\n    // If we are replacing the current window with the logon page, initialize the logon page UI now\r\n    //\r\n    if (a_fRC)\r\n        initLogon();\r\n\r\n    // Otherwise we need to find the window to replace with the logon page and redirect that window\r\n    //\r\n    else\r\n        redir();\r\n};\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// Initializes the logon page\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction initLogon()\r\n{\r\n    try\r\n    {\r\n        //\r\n        // we don\'t call document.execCommand("ClearAuthenticationCache","false"); anymore. As a part of the Pending-Notification\r\n        // infrastructure, we are making a change to make sure startpage does not get loaded more than once. This solution is cookie\r\n        // based. This execCommand was clearing all cookies in the scenario when a user logged on from a child window during an\r\n        // FBA timeout. We do not want that to happen anymore. If this breaks anything, we may need to consider a different solution.\r\n        //\r\n        // Old Comments:\r\n        // If the "Clear the Authentication Cache" flag is set to true and\r\n        // we are coming from the logoff page , clear the cache. See bug 41770 and 5840 for details.\r\n        //\r\n\r\n        // Logoff the S-Mime control.\r\n        //\r\n        LogoffMime();\r\n    }\r\n    catch (e) { }\r\n\r\n    // Check for username cookie\r\n    //\r\n    var re = /(^|; )logondata=acc=([0|1])&lgn=([^;]+)(;|$)/;\r\n    var rg = re.exec(document.cookie);\r\n\r\n    if (rg)\r\n    {\r\n        // Fill in username, set security to private, and restore the "use basic" selection\r\n        //\r\n\r\n        gbid("username").value = rg[3];\r\n\r\n        try\r\n        {\r\n            var signInErrorElement = gbid("signInErrorDiv");\r\n            if (signInErrorElement)\r\n            {\r\n                signInErrorElement.focus();\r\n            }\r\n            else\r\n            {\r\n                gbid("password").focus();\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n        catch (e)\r\n        {}\r\n\r\n        if (gbid("chkPrvt") && !gbid("chkPrvt").checked)\r\n        {\r\n            gbid("chkPrvt").click();\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (rg[2] == "1" && gbid("chkBsc"))\t// chkBsc doesn\'t exist if the request comes from ECP\r\n            gbid("chkBsc").click();\r\n\r\n    }\r\n    else\r\n    {\r\n        // The variable g_fFcs is set to false when the password gains focus,\r\n        // so that we don\'t accidentally set focus to the username field while\r\n        // the user is typing their password\r\n        //\r\n        if (g_fFcs)\r\n        {\r\n            try\r\n            {\r\n                gbid("username").focus();\r\n            }\r\n            catch (e)\r\n            { }\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    // OWA Premium currently supports\r\n    // IE 7+, Safari 3+, Firefox 3+ for Windows / Mac\r\n    if (IsOwaPremiumBrowser() && gbid("chkBsc"))\t// chkBsc doesn\'t exist if the request comes from ECP\r\n        gbid("chkBsc").disabled = false;\r\n\r\n    // Are cookies enabled?\r\n    //\r\n    var sCN = "cookieTest";\r\n\r\n    document.cookie = sCN + "=1";\r\n    var cookiesEnabled = document.cookie.indexOf(sCN + "=") != -1;\r\n\r\n    if (cookiesEnabled == false)\r\n    {\r\n        shw(gbid("cookieMsg"));\r\n        hd(gbid("lgnDiv"));\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    // Show the public/private warning message\r\n    clkSec();\r\n}\r\n\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// Finds the frame we want to load the logon page into, and then loads it there\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction redir()\r\n{\r\n    var o = window;\r\n\r\n    // If we\'re in a dialog, open a logon window and close the dialog - this\r\n    // basically inlines a version of opnWin() so that we don\'t need to include\r\n    // uglobal.js in logon.aspx\r\n    //\r\n    try\r\n    {\r\n        if (o.dialogArguments)\r\n        {\r\n            var sWN = new String(Math.round(Math.random() * 100000));\r\n            var sF = "toolbar=0,location=0,directories=0,status=1,menubar=0,scrollbars=1,resizable=1,width=800,height=600";\r\n            var iT = Math.round((screen.availHeight - 600) / 2);\r\n            var iL = Math.round((screen.availWidth - 800) / 2);\r\n            sF += ",top=" + iT + ",left=" + iL;\r\n\r\n            // Fix for E12 14838.  Need to open this window from the window that opened us, because opening it from this dialog\r\n            // which we are about to close can cause the auth cookies to not propagate to the window that opened this dialog.\r\n            //\r\n            var op = o.dialogArguments.opener;\r\n            try\r\n            {\r\n                if (op)\r\n                    op.open(a_sCW, sWN, sF);\r\n            }\r\n            catch (e)\r\n            { }\r\n\r\n            o.close();\r\n            return;\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n    catch (e)\r\n    { }\r\n\r\n    // The url to redirect to after logon\r\n    //\r\n    var sUrl = a_sUrl;\r\n\r\n    // Find the outermost OWA frame\r\n    //\r\n    while (1)\r\n    {\r\n        try\r\n        {\r\n            // Try to move up one window/frame\r\n            //\r\n            if (!(o.frameElement && o.frameElement.ownerDocument))\r\n                break;\r\n\r\n            var oF = o.frameElement.ownerDocument.parentWindow || // IE name\r\n                    o.frameElement.ownerDocument.defaultView;     // W3C name\r\n\r\n            // If we\'re not in an OWA/ECP window, we\'ve found the frame to replace\r\n            //\r\n            if (!oF || (!oF.g_fOwa && !oF.g_fEcp))\r\n                break;\r\n\r\n            // Move up a frame\r\n            //\r\n            o = oF;\r\n\r\n            // We\'re replacing something other than the current frame,  we\'ll just\r\n            // log back in to the default start page if the frame doesn\'t provide a url\r\n            //  for relogon. The frame should provide a global method GetReloadUrl\r\n            // if it wants to keep current state.\r\n            // $NOTES: ECP needs to keep the current frame state after re-logon.\r\n            sUrl = o.GetReloadUrl ? "&url=" + encodeURIComponent(o.GetReloadUrl()) : "";\r\n        }\r\n        // Either we\'re at the top, or access was denied - either way, stop\r\n        //\r\n        catch (e)\r\n        {\r\n            break;\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    // See if the window was opened by another window\r\n    //\r\n    try\r\n    {\r\n        var oW = o.opener;\r\n\r\n        // If it was opened by another OWA/ECP window, take it over\r\n        //\r\n        if (oW && (oW.g_fOwa || oW.g_fEcp))\r\n        {\r\n            // Center and resize the window\r\n            //\r\n            var iX = Math.round((screen.availWidth - 800) / 2);\r\n            var iY = Math.round((screen.availHeight - 600) / 2);\r\n            o.moveTo(iX, iY);\r\n            o.resizeTo(800, 600);\r\n\r\n            // Close the window after logging in\r\n            //\r\n            sUrl = "&url=" + encodeURIComponent(a_sCW);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n    // We don\'t have access to the opener window, so it couldn\'t be part of OWA\r\n    //\r\n    catch (e) { }\r\n\r\n    // Redirect the window\r\n    //\r\n    if (o.navigate)\r\n        o.navigate(a_sLgn + sUrl);\r\n    else\r\n        o.location = a_sLgn + sUrl;\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// Show an element\r\n/// </summary>\r\n/// <param name="o">Element to show</param>\r\nfunction shw(o)\r\n{\r\n    o.style.display = "";\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// Hide an element\r\n/// </summary>\r\n/// <param name="o">Element to hide</param>\r\nfunction hd(o)\r\n{\r\n    o.style.display = "none";\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnClick handler for the show private explanation \r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction clkSecExp(id)\r\n{\r\n    var o = gbid(id);\r\n\r\n    if (o.tagName == "IMG")\r\n        o = o.parentNode;\r\n\r\n    switch (o)\r\n    {\r\n        case gbid("lnkShwSec"):\r\n            hd(gbid("lnkShwSec"));\r\n            shw(gbid("lnkHdSec"));\r\n            shw(gbid("prvtExp"));\r\n            gbid("lnkHdSec").focus();\r\n            break;\r\n        case gbid("lnkHdSec"):\r\n            shw(gbid("lnkShwSec"));\r\n            hd(gbid("lnkHdSec"));\r\n            hd(gbid("prvtExp"));\r\n            gbid("lnkShwSec").focus();\r\n            break;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// onkeydown handler for the show private explanation \r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction kdSecExp(id)\r\n{\r\n    // When user press space bar, we shall treat it as click.\r\n    if (window.event.keyCode == 32)\r\n    {\r\n        clkSecExp(id);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnClick handler for the security radio buttons\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction clkSec()\r\n{\r\n    if (gbid("chkPrvt") == null) {\r\n\r\n        // If the private checkbox is not present in the page there is nothing we should do here\r\n        //\r\n        return;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    // Display/hide the warning message\r\n    //\r\n    var c = gbid("chkPrvt").checked;\r\n\r\n    gbid("prvtWrn").style.display = c ? "" : "none";\r\n\r\n    // Update flags and username cookie\r\n    //\r\n    if (c)\r\n    {\r\n        document.logonForm["flags"].value |= 4;\r\n    }\r\n    else\r\n    {\r\n        document.logonForm["flags"].value &= ~4;\r\n\r\n        // Remove the cookie by expiring it\r\n        //\r\n        var oD = new Date();\r\n        oD.setTime(oD.getTime() - 9999);\r\n        document.cookie = "logondata=; expires=" + oD.toUTCString();\r\n        document.cookie = "PrivateComputer=; path=/; expires=" + oD.toUTCString();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnClick handler for the use owa basic checkbox\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction clkBsc()\r\n{\r\n    // Display/hide the warning message\r\n    //\r\n    var c = gbid("chkBsc").checked;\r\n    gbid("bscExp").style.display = c ? "" : "none";\r\n\r\n    if (c)\r\n        document.logonForm.flags.value |= 1;\r\n    else\r\n        document.logonForm.flags.value &= ~1;\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunction checkSubmit(e) {\r\n    if (e && e.keyCode == 13) {\r\n        // Since we are explicitly handling the click prevent the default implicit submit  \r\n        if (e.preventDefault) {\r\n            e.preventDefault();\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        clkLgn();\r\n    }\r\n} \r\n\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnClick handler for the logon button\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction clkLgn()\r\n{\r\n    // Add performance marker for Logon page as the item name defined in the spec:\r\n    // http://exweb/14/Specs/E14 Spec Library/Client side perf marker definition.xlsx\r\n    //\r\n    addPerfMarker("Logon.Start");\r\n\r\n    var p = false;\r\n\r\n    if (gbid("chkPrvt")) {\r\n        p = p | gbid("chkPrvt").checked;\r\n    }\r\n    else\r\n    {\r\n        p = true;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    // If security is set to private, add a cookie to persist username and basic setting\r\n    // Cookie format: logondata=acc=<1 or 0>&lgn=<username>\r\n    //\r\n    if (p)\r\n    {\r\n        // Calculate the expires time for two weeks\r\n        //\r\n        var oD = new Date();\r\n        oD.setTime(oD.getTime() + 2 * 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000);\r\n        var sA = "acc=" + (gbid("chkBsc") && gbid("chkBsc").checked ? 1 : 0);\r\n        var sL = "lgn=" + gbid("username").value;\r\n        document.cookie = "logondata=" + sA + "&" + sL + "; expires=" + oD.toUTCString();\r\n        document.cookie = "PrivateComputer=true; path=/; expires=" + oD.toUTCString();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    if (gbid("showPasswordCheck").checked)\r\n    {\r\n        passwordElement = gbid("password");\r\n        passwordTextElement = gbid("passwordText");\r\n        passwordElement.value = passwordTextElement.value;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    // We clean the post back cookie in order to indicate that the credentials post is legitimate (and not history postback)\r\n    //\r\n    document.cookie = "PBack=0; path=/";\r\n    document.logonForm.submit();\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnClick handler for the retry button\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction clkRtry()\r\n{\r\n    window.location.reload();\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// OnClick handler for the ok button after changing password (will go to owa/)\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction clkReLgn()\r\n{\r\n    window.location.href = \'../\';\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// GetElementByID from Document\r\n/// </summary>\r\n/// <param name="s">Id of the Element</param>\r\nfunction gbid(s)\r\n{\r\n    return document.getElementById(s);\r\n}\r\n\r\n/// <summary>\r\n/// Is the Client IE 7, Safari 3, Firefox 3 or Above\r\n/// Note The rules should match owa\\bin\\core\\Utlities.cs@IsDownLevelClient\r\n/// </summary>\r\nfunction IsOwaPremiumBrowser()\r\n{\r\n    var ua = navigator.userAgent;\r\n    var av = navigator.appVersion;\r\n    var mac = (av.indexOf(\'Mac\') != -1);\r\n    var win = ((av.indexOf(\'Win\') != -1) || (av.indexOf(\'NT\') != -1));\r\n\r\n    // If you change the follow browser check logic, change utility.js as well.\r\n    // We have duplicate logic because otherwise logon page must include more code than necessary.\r\n    //\r\n    var ie = (ua.indexOf("MSIE ") != -1);\r\n    var firefox = (ua.indexOf("Firefox/") != -1 && ua.indexOf("Gecko/") != -1 && Array.every);\r\n    var safari = (ua.indexOf("Safari") != -1 && ua.indexOf("WebKit") != -1);\r\n    var version = 2.0;\r\n\r\n    if (ie)\r\n    {\r\n        version = parseFloat(ua.replace(/^.*MSIE /, \'\'));\r\n    }\r\n    else if (firefox)\r\n    {\r\n        version = parseFloat(ua.replace(/^.*Firefox\\//, \'\'));\r\n    }\r\n    else if (safari)\r\n    {\r\n        version = parseFloat(ua.replace(/^.*Version\\//, \'\'));\r\n    }\r\n    else\r\n    {\r\n        version = parseInt(av);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    if (win)\r\n    {\r\n        if (ie)\r\n            return (version >= 7.0);\r\n        else if (safari)\r\n            return (version >= 3.0);\r\n        else if (firefox)\r\n            return (version >= 3.0);\r\n    }\r\n    else if (mac)\r\n parseInt(tab[i].offsetWidth);\ntabTotalWidth = tabTotalWidth + LiWidth;\n}\n$("#_totalTabWidth").val(tabTotalWidth);\nvar class3MenuUl = $("ul",class3MenuContainer);\nif ( tabTotalWidth > ContainerWidth )\n{\nclass3MenuUl.css("width", 5000);\n$("#scrollLeftBtn,#scrollRightBtn").addClass("EnableScrollBtn");\nvar nowScrollLocation = $("#_Menu3Location").text();\nif tabTotalWidth-ContainerWidth;\n}\nclass3MenuContainer.scrollLeft(nowScrollLocation);\nStatusOfLRBtnOf3MenuHandle(nowScrollLocation);\n}\nelse\n{\n$("#scrollLeftBtn").removeClass("scrollLeftBtn");\n$("#scrollRightBtn").removeClass("scrollRightBtn");\n}\n}\nfunction {\n\tdisplay: inline !important;\n\tborder: none !important;\n\tbox-shadow: none !important;\n\theight: 1em !important;\n\twidth: 1em !important;\n\tmargin: 0 .07em !important;\n\tvertical-align: !important;}\n\n\n \n \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nNews\nIntroduction\nParticipants\nSecurity\nUser Guide\n\nFAQ\n\nAvailable software\n\n\n\n\nToolbox\n\nLooking Glass\nRESTful API\nRING SQA\nHealth monitoring\n\n\nContact\n\nApplication form\n\n\nPatrons\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nMotivation \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 \xa0 Application Form\nI’ve noticed that there are a lot of friendly ‘shell access’ exchange deals\xa0between network operators. This makes it easier for parties to debug\xa0network issues and troubleshoot ‘from the outside’. A point of view outside\xa0your network is absolutely essential, seeing what others see is a useful\xa0thing with a variety of network problems. Well known examples are ‘it works\xa0for even numbered ip address, but not for odd numbered ip address via this\xa0and this route’.\nTo encourage and provide a streamlined way of cooperating I introduce the\xa0“NLNOG RING”. In essence the deal is very simple: you make a (virtual) machine available to\xa0the RING, and you gain access on all servers which are part of the project,\xa0hence the name “RING”.\nA great example would be to launch a traceroute from 80 servers in different\xa0networks and quickly get the results instead of waiting till somebody has\xa0the time to run some tests for you.\nParticipation\nParticipation is open to everybody who meets the following requirements:\n\nYou are a network operator\nThe organisation you work for has BGP routers connected to the\xa0“Default Free Zone” and maybe even IXP’s.\nYour organisation has its own ASN, IPv4 and IPv6 prefix(es).\nYou have enable or configure rights on those routers.\nYou are involved in the networkers community.\nYou have permission from your organisation to become involved in the NLNOG RING.\n\nApplying for the RING\nAdmission to the project is discretionary and judged by perceived value for the RING as a whole. If your application is for an additional machine in a covered ASN, please contact us first.\nIf you would like to join, please fill out our application form.\nMachine\nThe following requirements are mandatory:\n\nClean Ubuntu 18.04 Bionic Beaver 64-bit (amd64/x86_64) Server Edition installation (no special\xa0packages are required except openssh-server)\n64 bit CPU\n1 globally reachable and unique statically configured IPv4 address\n1 globally reachable and unique statically configured IPv6 address\nno packet filtering between your RING node and the internet\nYou are willing to give full sudo access to the Ring-Admins\xa0(we will get to the security considerations later in this document)\n\nThe following suggestions are indicative:\n\n1 core or CPU\n20 gigabyte disk space\nat least 1024 megabyte RAM, but more is better\n10mbit NIC (more is fine)\n\n(please decide for yourself what is appropiate, the machine will be\xa0a mere shell server managed by ansible)\nManagement\nAll regular nodes (machines provided by organisations) are managed\xa0through a centralized ansible system. Ring-Admins will take care of software\xa0and security updates, installation and user management. The goal is to make\xa0it as easy as possible for organisations to provide a machine and not worry\xa0about it afterwards.\nMachine owners are allowed and encouraged to install software which they\xa0deem necessary to comply with the standards of their organisation, examples\xa0are: n2, backup programs or a snmp daemon.\nAbuse\nThis RING is based on mutual trust: “you give me access I give you\xa0access”. We hope this model is strong enough to be viable. Abuse of the\xa0resources provided by the NLNOG RING is absolutely forbidden and\xa0we apply a ‘zero tolerance’ policy. This means that after one abuse\xa0incident you will be permantly banned from the RING. Through\xa0extensive logging and limitating the rights users have on other\xa0people’s systems we also hope to prevent abuse. For more information\xa0regarding the security of machines please see the Security section of this website.\nAcknowledgements\nA non-exhaustive list of people involved in the design and management of the NLNOG RING since its inception: Peter van Dijk, Teun Vink, Edwin Hermans, Martin Pels, Pieter Lexis, Matt Griswold and me.\nIf you have any questions please do not hesitate to contact us. Contact information can be found on the Contact page.\nKind regards,\nJob Snijders\n\n\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\xa0\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nComments are closed.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\n\n \n \n \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNLNOG RING\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\n\n\n\nPages\n\nNews\nIntroduction\nParticipants\nSecurity\nUser Guide\nToolbox\nContact\nPatrons\n\n\n\n\n\nThe Latest\n\n\n\nMatthias Fetzer (UA) joined the RING\nMatthias Fetzer – AS 205365 – joined the RING today. sieć czujników PM 2,5 i PM 10 \n\n\n\n\xa0Samodzielnie zmierz jakość powietrza w swojej okolicy.\xa0\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nZbuduj własny czujnik\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nKim jesteśmy?OK Lab Stuttgart jest częścią programu Code for Germany w ramach Open Knowledge Foundation Germany. Celem fundacji jest promowanie rozwoju transparentności, otwartych danych oraz swobodnego dostępu do nauki tworzonej przez obywateli.Regionalne grupy projektantów, programistów i dziennikarzy spotykają się regularnie w celu rozwoju aplikacji, które informując wspierają społeczeństwo czyniąc działania rządu bardziej zrozumiałymi i transparentnymi.W Polsce czujniki luftdaten, promowane są przez partnerstwo składające się z Koduj dla Polski (Fundacja ePaństwo), Warszawskiego Hackerspace, Warszawskiego Alarmu Smogowego\xa0oraz aktywistki i aktywistów, którym zależy.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nCzym jest luftdaten.info?Dopuszczalne stężenia pyłów zawieszonych są regularnie przekraczane w miastach.W jaki sposób jakość powietrza może być zmierzona i zwizualizowana?Jaki wpływ ma duży ruch uliczny na „twoje” powietrze?Jak wysokie jest stężenie pyłów w miejscu zamieszkania?Zajmujemy się takimi problemami przez budowanie mierników zapylenia i wizualizację tych danych by pokazać całościowy obraz. Dane Luftadaten są dostępne na licencji: \xa0Database Contents License (DbCL) v1.0. Mapa\xa0 może i powinna być dalej rozwijana przez społeczność użytkowników.Oficjalne dane o jakości powietrza w Polsce udostępnia Inspekcja Ochrony Środowiska\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nNauka obywatelska, dołącz!OK Lab Stuttgart jest zaangażowany w pomiary pyłów PM10 i PM2,5 w ramach projektu lufddaten.info. Podobnie jak i tysiące ludzi na świecie możesz zainstalować zbudowany przez siebie czujnik na zewnątrz domu. Na podstawie stale przesyłanych danych nasza strona tworzy aktualną mapę stanu zanieczyszczeń. Dzięki temu ten drobny pył staje się widzialny.Spotkania/pomoc w montażuSprawdź na stronie Koduj dla Polski lub na stronie lokalnego Alarmu Smogowego czy w okolicy nie jest planowana akcja wsparcia myCart();\n\n                    }\n                });\n            }\n\n            function updateCart(attribute_id,productCount){\n                $.ajax({\n                    url: "http://13.234.156.133/update-cart",\n                    type: \'GET\',\n                    data:{\'attribute_id\':attribute_id,\'quantity\':productCount},\n                    dataType: \'json\',\n myCart();\n\n                    }\n                });\n            }\n\n\n\n            $(document).on("click",".remove-from-cart",function() {\n            let delete_id = $(this).attr(\'attribute_id\');\n                removeFromCart(delete_id);\n\n            });\n\n            $(document).ready(function(){\n                $(\'.count\').prop(\'disabled\', true);\n                $(document).on(\'click\',\'.plus\',function(){\n                    let productCount = $(this).attr(\'val\');\n                    productCount++;\n                    let attribute_id = $(this).attr(\'attribute_id\');\n                    updateCart(attribute_id,productCount);\n\n                });\n\n\n\n                $(document).on(\'click\',\'.minus\',function(){\n                    let productCount = $(this).attr(\'val\');\n                    let attribute_id = $(this).attr(\'attribute_id\');\n                    if(--productCount==0){\n
